# Chapter 1 — Combinator

## Addition Principle
If you’re choosing between different options — like it’s either this or that — you add the possibilities.  
It’s not about doing both; it’s picking one path or the other.

Formula: Add them  
Example: 3 soda options or 5 juice options → 3 + 5 = 8

---

## Multiplication Principle
If you’re making independent choices in sequence — one after another — you multiply.  
Think of it as "this and that," like building a combo meal.

Formula: Multiply them  
Example: 3 drinks × 4 desserts → 3 × 4 = 12

---

## Permutation (all n)
If you’re arranging all items and the order matters, that’s a permutation of all n.  
It’s about ordering everything — no repeats.

Formula: n!  
Example: Arrange 5 books → 5! = 120

---

## Permutation (k of n)
If you’re only arranging part of the set (top k spots) and order matters, it’s still a permutation — but only for those k positions.  
You can’t reuse any item.

Formula: P(n, k) = n! / (n−k)!  
Example: Top 3 of 10 runners → 10 × 9 × 8 = 720

---

## Permutation with Repetition
If order matters and you can repeat, it’s all about powering — every spot has the same number of options.

Formula: n^k  
Example: 4-digit PIN → 10^4 = 10,000

---

## Combination
If order doesn’t matter and you can’t repeat, that’s a combination.  
You only care about which ones, not in what order.

Formula: C(n, k) = n! / (k!(n−k)!)  
Example: Pick 5 people out of 10 → 10 choose 5 = 252

---

## Combination with Repetition
If order doesn’t matter but you can repeat, like scooping ice cream flavors, use this formula.

Formula: C(n+k−1, k)  
Example: 6 flavors, 3 scoops → C(8, 3) = 56

---

## Distribution A — Identical items, distinct boxes (empty ok)
Split identical items (like candies) into different boxes or people, and it’s okay for some boxes to be empty.

Formula: C(k+n−1, n−1)  
Example: 10 candies → 4 kids → C(13, 3) = 286

---

## Distribution B — Identical items, distinct boxes (none empty)
Same idea, but this time everyone gets at least one.  
No empty boxes allowed.

Formula: C(k−1, n−1)  
Example: 10 candies → 4 kids ≥ 1 each → C(9, 3) = 84

---

## Distribution C — Identical items, distinct boxes (min aᵢ each)
Each person or box has a minimum requirement.  
Subtract those minimums first, then distribute the rest freely.

Formula: C(k−Σaᵢ + n−1, n−1)  
Example: (x₁≥2, x₃≥3, x₄≥1)

---

## Distribution D — Identical items, distinct boxes (max bᵢ)
If every box has a maximum limit, use Inclusion–Exclusion to remove cases that break the cap.

Formula: Inclusion–Exclusion  
Example: Candy limits → count all, then subtract the overlaps

---

## Distribution E — Distinct items, distinct boxes (empty ok)
If items and boxes are distinct, and empty boxes are fine, every item has n choices.

Formula: n^k  
Example: 3 candies → 2 kids → 2^3 = 8

---

## Distribution F — Distinct items, distinct boxes (none empty)
Every box must get at least one item.  
Uses Stirling numbers of the second kind or Inclusion–Exclusion.

Formula: n! S(k, n) or Σ(−1)^j C(n, j)(n−j)^k  
Example: 5 candies → 3 kids (no empty boxes) → 150 ways

---

## Inclusion–Exclusion Principle
Use this when counting cases that overlap (like multiples).  
Add singles, subtract doubles, add triples, and so on.

Formula: Add singles − doubles + triples − …  
Example: Numbers divisible by 2, 3, or 5 → add singles, subtract overlaps

---

## Binomial Theorem
When expanding (a+b)^n, each term uses a binomial coefficient.  
It shows all ways a and b can appear across n positions.

Formula: (a+b)^n = Σ C(n, k) a^(n−k) b^k  
Example: (x+1)^4 = x⁴ + 4x³ + 6x² + 4x + 1